{{other uses|Braničevo (disambiguation)}}
{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}
'''Braničevo''' ([[Serbian Cyrillic]]: Браничево, {{IPA-sh|brǎnitʃɛʋɔ|pron}}) is a geographical region in east-central [[Serbia]]. It is mostly situated in the [[Braničevo District]].

==History==
[[File:Map of the Despotate of Stefan Lazarevic 1422.svg|thumbnail|Town of Braničevo in the Serbian Despotate in 1422.]]
In the 9th century, a Slavic (Serb<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?ei=_XGmUZ-zDYGp7Aax1IDwBQ&hl=en&id=-YMMAQAAMAAJ&dq=srpsko+pleme+brani%C4%8Devci&q=%22oba+srpska+plemena%2C+Brani%C4%8Devci+i+Timo-+%C4%8Dani%22#search_anchor]</ref>) tribe known as [[Braničevci]] are mentioned living in the region. In this time, the town named [[Braničevo (town)|Braničevo]] also existed in the area, at the estuary of the river [[Mlava]] into [[Danube]]. In the Early Middle Ages, Braničevo became a part of the [[First Bulgarian Empire]]. After the conquest of Bulgaria, the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]] established the [[Theme of Sirmium]] in the wider region south of the river [[Danube]]. Syrmia, and hence Braničevo, came to be contested between [[Kingdom of Hungary]] on the one side, and the [[Byzantine Empire]] and the [[Second Bulgarian Empire]] (after its independence from the Byzantines) on the other. In the 13th century the Hungarians established the [[Banate of Braničevo]] (Banovina of Braničevo), but later in the century two local Bulgarian rulers, [[Darman and Kudelin]], became independent and ruled over Braničevo and [[Kučevo]]. In 1291, they were defeated by the [[Serbs|Serbian]] king, [[Stefan Dragutin]], who joined Braničevo to his [[Kingdom of Syrmia|Syrmian Kingdom]]. Under his rule the town of Braničevo became a seat of the [[Eparchy]] of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]].<ref name=Fine>{{cite book|last=Fine|first=John V.A.|title=The Late Medieval Balkans: a critical survey from the late twelfth century to the Ottoman conquest|year=1994|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=9780472082605|page=261|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LvVbRrH1QBgC}}</ref> The region later belonged to subsequent Serbian states, until it was conquered by the [[Ottoman Empire]] in the 15th century. In the 14th century, the region was in a possession of local rulers from the [[House of Rastislalić]]. During the Ottoman rule, Braničevo was part of the [[Sanjak of Smederevo]], and since 19th century, it is again part of the [[Serbia]]n state.

